```json
{
  "name": "INJONGO",
  "full_name": "INJONGO — A Multicultural Intent Detection and Slot-Filling Dataset for African Languages",
  "year": 2025,
  "domain": "Intent detection and slot-filling for African-language task-oriented dialogue",
  "porting_strategy": "ground_up",
  "languages": [
    "am",
    "yo",
    "ig",
    "ha",
    "sw",
    "xh",
    "zu",
    "sn",
    "st",
    "tw",
    "ee",
    "wo",
    "lin",
    "kin",
    "orm",
    "tir",
    "en"
  ],
  "primary_region": "Sub-Saharan Africa",
  "description": "INJONGO is the first large-scale multicultural intent detection and slot-filling (ID-SF)\ndataset covering 16 African languages plus English. It contains 3,200 annotated utterances\nper African language across 5 domains (Banking, Home, Travel, Utility, Kitchen & Dining),\n40 intent categories, and 23 slot types. Utterances were elicited from native speakers with\nexplicit instruction to replace Western entities with locally appropriate cultural equivalents,\nrather than translating from English. The dataset covers languages from two dominant African\nlanguage families: 13 Niger-Congo and 3 Afro-Asiatic, and is positioned as a culturally\ngrounded alternative to Western-centric NLU benchmarks such as CLINC and MASSIVE.\n",
  "documentation_excerpts": "## Key characteristics relevant to validity analysis:\n\n### Input Ontology\nINJONGO defines the ID-SF task as mapping user requests to predefined semantic categories\nand extracting slot entities within task-oriented dialogue systems [Q2, Q3]. The taxonomy\nencompasses 40 intent categories organized across five domains — Banking, Home, Travel,\nUtility, and Kitchen & Dining — explicitly selected from a pool of 150 CLINC intents as\n\"most suitable to African contexts\" [Q39, Q117]. Cross-lingual transfer experiments compare\nthe African-centric INJONGO taxonomy against Western-centric CLINC, providing direct\nevidence that the ontology was designed with pan-African applicability as an explicit\ncriterion [Q101]. Encoder-only, encoder-decoder, and LLM-based model categories are all\nevaluated, reflecting a broad task framing [Q61].\n\nThe benchmark explicitly acknowledges that its domain coverage is constrained: \"healthcare\nand education\" are identified as absent but \"essential for real-world applications\" [Q107].\nAnalogously, sub-intents specific to Ethiopian utility workflows — prepaid/STS meter\ntop-ups, mobile-money platforms such as Telebirr or CBE Birr, tiered-pricing disputes, and\noutage-schedule reporting — are not documented as represented. The closest comparable\nbenchmark in African NLP, MasakhaNER, is noted to cover only four coarse entity types and\n\"are not fine-grained and well adapted to several domains such as banking and travel\" [Q25],\nunderscoring that INJONGO is a genuine ontological advance but still bounded by its 40-intent\nceiling. The fixed uniform distribution of examples across intents is also acknowledged as\npotentially unrepresentative of real-world interaction frequencies [Q111].\n\n### Input Content\nThe dataset was designed to address two documented failings of prior multilingual NLU datasets:\nthe translationese effect and cultural irrelevance [Q13]. Rather than translating English\nutterances, annotators were given sample CLINC sentences for a given intent and asked to\ngenerate culturally relevant alternatives with locally appropriate slot entities [Q37]. The\nXhosa annotator example — substituting South African currency (Rand), and banks (FNB, Absa)\nfor generic entities [Q40, Q41] — illustrates this cultural grounding principle. The English\ncomponent consists of 1,779 practice utterances generated by annotators across all 16 African\nlanguages, rather than canonical Western English [Q58, Q59], and a 4,000-instance CLINC sample\nis retained only for contrastive evaluation [Q60].\n\nCoverage spans 13 Niger-Congo and 3 Afro-Asiatic languages [Q33], with speaker populations\nranging from Swahili (98 million) to Wolof (5 million) [Q34]. Amharic is one of the three\nAfro-Asiatic languages, and the dataset is described as \"the first large-scale multicultural\nintent detection and slot-filling dataset covering 16 African languages\" [Q4], correcting\nthe prior state-of-the-art (MASSIVE) which included only three African languages and left\nmany utterances \"culturally irrelevant to the target language communities\" [Q14]. Performance\ndifferences across languages are partly attributed to differential availability of monolingual\nweb data [Q88], with Swahili (1 billion+ tokens) achieving near-English performance [Q89],\nimplying Amharic may be systematically disadvantaged relative to higher-resource African\nlanguages. Code-switching between Amharic and English is not documented as an explicit\ndesign criterion or measured as a property of the Amharic split.\n\n### Input Form\nThe benchmark is text-only [Q43], which aligns with the Telegram and SMS deployment channels.\nThe annotation was performed in native script on the LabelStudio platform [Q43], and the\nEthiopic (Ge'ez) script is the expected representation for Amharic. The paper does not\ndocument script normalization procedures or confirm Unicode encoding standards for the\nAmharic instances. Inference infrastructure accommodates both API-based closed-source\nmodels (GPT-4o, Gemini 1.5 Pro [Q131]) and open-source models via vLLM and TGI [Q132],\nall under FP32 precision on NVIDIA H100/L40S GPUs [Q129]. The dataset is released under\nCC BY 4.0 [Q23] and partitioned 70/10/20% for train/dev/test, stratified by intent [Q57].\nNo documentation of SMS-specific signal degradation, romanized Amharic (Amharic written\nin Latin characters), or Ethiopic-Arabic numeral mixing is provided.\n\n### Output Ontology\nThe slot label ontology was initially set at 34 types [Q118], subsequently reduced to 23\nfinal types by merging similar or low-frequency categories [Q54, Q55, Q119]. The complete\nfinal set is enumerated in the annotation guide: ACCOUNT_TYPE, ARTIST_NAME, BANK_NAME,\nBILL_TYPE, CALENDAR_EVENT, CITY_OR_PROVINCE, COUNTRY, CURRENCY, DATE, DISH_OR_FOOD,\nHOTEL_NAME, LANGUAGE_NAME, MEAL_PERIOD, MONEY, MUSIC_GENRE, NUMBER, PAYMENT_COMPANY,\nPERSONAL_NAME, PLACE_NAME, RESTAURANT_NAME, SHOPPING_ITEM, SONG_NAME, TIME [Q144]. Several\nof these (ACCOUNT_TYPE, BANK_NAME, MONEY, PAYMENT_COMPANY, CITY_OR_PROVINCE, PLACE_NAME)\nare directly relevant to Ethiopian utility billing contexts. However, the ontology does not\ninclude a dedicated METER_ID, UTILITY_ACCOUNT_NUMBER, or ADDRESS_SUBUNIT type that would\ncapture kebele numbers or informal neighborhood designations common in Ethiopian utility\naccounts. Nine infrequent slot types (from NATIONALITY through PLUG TYPE) were eliminated\nduring preprocessing [Q52], and no justification is provided for why these rather than\nutility-specific slots were excluded.\n\nThe 40-intent taxonomy is described as selected from 150 CLINC intents as best suited to\nAfrican contexts [Q39], but the specific intent labels are not fully enumerated in the\nregistry beyond domain-level examples (\"transfer,\" \"pay bill,\" \"exchange rate,\" \"book\nflight\"). Intent detection performance for open LLMs is poor, attributed partly to \"the\nlarge label space (i.e. 40) for the classification task\" [Q86], suggesting the 40-intent\nceiling may itself introduce measurement noise for deployment systems with narrower scopes.\n\n### Output Content\nEach utterance was annotated by three independent native-speaker annotators to enable\nmajority-vote agreement checking [Q42, Q45]. The annotation process required two rounds\nof review to achieve consistent quality [Q109], and initial Fleiss' Kappa scores varied\nsubstantially across languages, from 0.618 (Zulu) to 0.934 (Shona) [Q47], with post-review\nscores reaching 0.912–1.00 across all languages [Q48]. The largest pre-to-post improvements\nwere in Sesotho (+0.327) and Zulu (+0.294) [Q49], and ambiguous slot types were identified\nas a primary source of disagreement [Q53].\n\nAnnotator demographics are partially documented: all utterances were generated by native\nspeakers [Q7], remuneration was managed through a Kenya-based logistics company at\nper-country rates [Q44], and a complete annotation guide with disambiguation rules was\ndeveloped [Q149]. The annotation guide specifies rules such as: temporal spans under one\nday → TIME, over one day → DATE [Q153, Q154]; bank name annotation excludes the word\n\"bank\" unless attached to the proper name (e.g., \"Ecobank\") [Q152]; bill-type annotation\nincludes the word \"bill\" as part of the span [Q155]; named place entities require explicit\nnaming (not generic \"mall\" or \"airport\") [Q156]. However, the paper does not document\nwhether Amharic annotators had domain familiarity with Ethiopian utility billing\nterminology (prepaid meter accounts, Telebirr transaction records, kebele-level address\nconventions), and the Kappa breakdown by language is not reported in detail sufficient\nto isolate Amharic-specific annotation quality. Ground-truth validity for the Ethiopian\nutility deployment should reflect validation by utility customer service agents and billing\nstaff, a population not represented in the annotation pool.\n\n### Output Form\nIntent detection is evaluated with accuracy and slot-filling with F1-score [Q84], averaged\nover five random seeds for fine-tuning [Q63] and five prompting templates for LLM evaluations\n[Q73]. The output format for slot-filling uses `$$` as a separator between entity type and\nvalue [Q146], and prompts are language-specific and tailored to task requirements [Q138].\nModels are instructed to return `$$` only if no entities are found [Q145], and annotators\nare instructed not to skip any utterance even if no entities are present [Q157]. The output\nrepresentation is thus a structured text string rather than a binary or probabilistic\nclassification, and the F1 metric is applied to this structured extraction task.\n\nThe benchmark confirms that \"slot-filling task is difficult for all LLMs including on English\"\n[Q85], with the highest average LLM performance at 33.3% F1 (GPT-4o) compared to the\nbest fine-tuned model's 85.6% F1 [Q19, Q78]. Supervised fine-tuning on Gemma 2 9B\noutperforms 4-shot prompting by +15.8 accuracy and +34.1 F1 [Q98]. The output modality\nis text throughout, matching the deployment context; no speech, image, or open-ended\ngeneration outputs are evaluated.\n",
